1. Single run analyses¶

1.1 Functions¶

1.1.1 Simulation run function¶

Below is the simulation function used for the generation of the single run analyses. The code used for our larger simulations (the simulation experiment and the sensitivity analyses) was run on a HPC so the function used there is not printed here (but available in our github repository). The functions used there and the one printed here are qualitatively the same. The code used in the simulation experiment...

  • ...generates different output: indicators as measured at the end of the run instead of at every tick.
  • ...measures timesteps differently: ticks are only counted at non-bot influence events to control for the difference in influence opportunity between models with a very active bot compared to those with a very inactive bot.
  • ..write its output directly to a separate file to accommodate parallel processing.
In [2]:
def simulation_run(bot_connectedness=.25,
                   bot_activation_rate=.25,
                   N=144,
                   K=12,
                   P=0,
                   return_activity_monitor=True,
                   return_graph=False,
                   max_ticks=100000,
                   seed=None):
    """
    This function
        1. Creates the Axelrod model as a NetworkX graph object with a bot
        2. Executes similarity biased influence between 
            a. the BOT and a randomly selected network neighbor (with p = bot_activation_rate)
            b. two randomly selected network neighbors (with p = 1-bot_activation_rate)
        3. Returns graph object when no further influence is possible (or after 100,000 ticks)
    """
    
    ## PHASE 1) INITIALIZATION
    
    # seed the run for replicability
    random.seed(seed)
    
    # generate the NetworkX graph object and intialize with F random categorical features with Q traits
    G = ds.generate_network("watts_strogatz_graph",n=N,k=K,p=P)
    ds.initialize_attributes(G, realization="random_categorical", num_features=3, num_traits=3)
    
    # add the bot to the graph
    agentlist = list(G.nodes())
    G.add_node("bot")
    G.nodes["bot"]["f01"] = 99    # Unique bot trait, used to track the bot's effectiveness
    G.nodes["bot"]["f02"] = 0
    G.nodes["bot"]["f03"] = 0
    
    # connect the bot to a proportion 'bot_connectedness' of the graph
    friends_of_bot = random.sample(agentlist, int(bot_connectedness * N))
    for j in friends_of_bot:
        G.add_edge("bot",j)
    
    # calculate the dissimilarity on all edges
    calculator = ds.dissimilarity_calculator.select_calculator("hamming")
    calculator.calculate_dissimilarity_networkwide(G)

    # store the indices of direct and indirect contacts of the bot
    shortest_paths = nx.shortest_path_length(G,'bot')
    agents_l1 = [key for key, val in shortest_paths.items() if val == 1]
    agents_l2 = [key for key, val in shortest_paths.items() if val >= 2]
    
    # initialize ticks, stop variable, and tickwise dictionaries for output
    ticks = 0
    stop = False
    bot_trait_count = [dict(count_l1=len(agents_l1),
                            count_l2=len(agents_l2))]
    activity_monitor = dict(success=[],
                            i_is_bot=[])

    ## PHASE 2) SIMULATION
    
    while(not stop):
        ticks += 1

        # choose sending agent
        if random.random() > bot_activation_rate:
            agent_i = ds.select_focal_agent(G,"random",agentlist=agentlist)
            activity_monitor['i_is_bot'].append(False)
        else:
            agent_i = "bot"
            activity_monitor['i_is_bot'].append(True)

        # choose receiving agent
        agent_j = ["bot"]
        while agent_j == ["bot"]:
            agent_j = [(random.choice([neighbor for neighbor in G[agent_i]]))]

        # exert influence and store whether influence was successful 
        activity_monitor['success'].append(
            ds.influence_sim.spread_influence(G,"axelrod",agent_i,agent_j,"one-to-one",calculator)
        )
        
        # store the diffusion of the unique bot trait among first and second (or more) degree contacts
        bot_trait_count.append({'count_l1': len([1 for i in agents_l1 if G.nodes[i]['f01']==99]) / len(agents_l1),
                                'count_l2': len([1 for i in agents_l2 if G.nodes[i]['f01']==99]) / len(agents_l2)})

        # stop the execution if condition is true
        if(not any([True for i,j,d in G.edges.data('dist') if 0.1 < d < .9])
          or ticks > max_ticks):
            if(return_graph):
                return G
            if(return_activity_monitor):
                return bot_trait_count, activity_monitor
            else:
                return bot_trait_count
            stop = True

def bot_diffusion_fig_horizontal(df,am):
    # data_transformation
    infl_succ_total = np.cumsum([1 if i else 0 for i in am['success']])
    infl_succ_bot = np.cumsum([i+j-1 if i else 0 for i,j in zip(am['i_is_bot'],am['success'])])
    infl_succ_agent = np.cumsum([i+j if not i else 0 for i,j in zip(am['i_is_bot'],am['success'])])

    fig = plt.figure(constrained_layout=True,figsize=[6,3])
    gs = gridspec.GridSpec(nrows=2, ncols=3, figure=fig)
    
    plt.tight_layout()

    # panel A
    fig_s1 = fig.add_subplot(gs[:, :-1])
    fig_s1.text(-0.12, 1.1, "A", transform=fig_s1.transAxes, fontsize=16, fontweight='bold', va='top', ha='right')
    #fig_s1.set_title('..1..')
    fig_s1.set_ylabel('proportion')
    fig_s1.set_xlabel('time')
    fig_s1.set_ylim([0,1])
    fig_s1.plot(df['count_l2'][1:],color='green',linewidth=2)
    fig_s1.plot(df['count_l1'][1:],color='red',linewidth=2)
    fig_s1.plot(
        list((df['count_l1'][1:] * (df['count_l1'][0] / 144) + 
              df['count_l2'][1:] * (df['count_l2'][0] / 144))),
        color='blue',linewidth=2)

    # panel B
    fig_s2 = fig.add_subplot(gs[0, -1])
    fig_s2.text(-0.12, 1.2, "B", transform=fig_s2.transAxes, fontsize=16, fontweight='bold', va='top', ha='right')
    #fig_s2.set_title('..2..')
    fig_s2.set_ylabel('count')
    fig_s2.set_xlabel('time')
    fig_s2.set_ylim([0,144])

    fig_s2.plot(df['count_l2'][1:] * df['count_l2'][0],color='green',linewidth=2)
    fig_s2.plot(df['count_l1'][1:] * df['count_l1'][0],color='red',linewidth=2)
    fig_s2.plot(
        list((df['count_l1'][1:] * df['count_l1'][0] + 
              df['count_l2'][1:] * df['count_l2'][0])),
        color='blue',linewidth=2)

    # panel C
    fig_s3 = fig.add_subplot(gs[1, -1])
    fig_s3.text(-0.12, 1.2, "C", transform=fig_s3.transAxes, fontsize=16, fontweight='bold', va='top', ha='right')
    #fig_s2.set_title('..3..')
    fig_s3.set_ylabel('activity')
    fig_s3.set_xlabel('time')
    fig_s3.plot(infl_succ_agent, color='red', linewidth=2)
    fig_s3.plot(infl_succ_bot, color='green', linewidth=2)
    fig_s3.plot(infl_succ_total, color='blue', linewidth=2)

    return fig

def activity_trans(am):
    infl_succ_total = np.cumsum([1 if i else 0 for i in am['success']])
    infl_succ_bot = np.cumsum([i+j-1 if i else 0 for i,j in zip(am['i_is_bot'],am['success'])])
    infl_succ_agent = np.cumsum([i+j if not i else 0 for i,j in zip(am['i_is_bot'],am['success'])])
    
    return(infl_succ_total, infl_succ_bot, infl_succ_agent)

# function to generate the network figures
def gen_network_fig(G):
    pos = nx.circular_layout([i for i in range(144) if i%2==0],1)
    pos.update(nx.circular_layout([i for i in range(144) if i%2==1],.8))
    pos['bot'] = [0,0]

    nodecol = ['r' if G.nodes[i]['f01'] == 99 else 'b' for i in G.nodes()]
    bin_col = plt.cm.get_cmap('binary', 4)
    edgecol = [bin_col(1 - G.edges[i]['dist']) for i in G.edges()]
    
    Gcopy = G.copy()
    Gcopy.remove_edges_from([i for i in G.edges() if G.edges[i]['dist'] == 1])
    nx.draw_networkx_edges(Gcopy, pos=pos, edge_color=edgecol)
    nx.draw_networkx_nodes(G, pos=pos, node_size=14, node_color=nodecol)

In [16]:
def create_heatgrids(df, dv='DiffTotal'):
    warnings.filterwarnings("ignore")
    
    # values to matrix with means for heatmap
    df = df[[dv,'BotActivationRate','BotConnectedness']]
    heatgrid_mean = df.groupby(['BotActivationRate','BotConnectedness']).mean()

    heatgrid_mean = np.asarray(heatgrid_mean)
    heatgrid_mean = heatgrid_mean.reshape(
        len(np.unique(results['BotActivationRate'])),
        len(np.unique(results['BotConnectedness']))
    )

    # values to matrix with variances for heatmap
    heatgrid_var = df.groupby(['BotActivationRate','BotConnectedness']).var()

    heatgrid_var = np.asarray(heatgrid_var)
    heatgrid_var = heatgrid_var.reshape(
        len(np.unique(results['BotActivationRate'])),
        len(np.unique(results['BotConnectedness']))
    )
    return(heatgrid_mean, heatgrid_var)

4.4 Directed graphs¶

The directed spatial random graph is constructed with the following function:

In [39]:
def directed_spatial_random_graph(num_agents=144, degree=12, proximity_weight=1, return_positions=False, seed=None):
    np.random.seed(seed)
    
    if type(degree) == int:
        degree_seq = [degree for i in range(num_agents)]
    elif type(degree) == list:
        if len(degree) == num_agents:
            degree_seq = degree
        else:
            raise ValueError('\'degree\' is not of length \'num_agents\'')
    else:
        raise ValueError('\'degree\' should be an integer or a list with length \'num_agents\'')
    if any([i >= num_agents for i in degree_seq]):
        degree_seq = [i if i < num_agents else (num_agents-1) for i in degree_seq]

    xypos = np.column_stack((np.random.uniform(0, 100, num_agents), np.random.uniform(0, 100, num_agents)))

    def dist(posA, posB, proximity_weight):  # returns the probability as a function of distance
        return np.exp(-proximity_weight * np.sqrt(np.sum((posA - posB) ** 2)))

    distmatrix = np.zeros((num_agents, num_agents))

    for i in range(num_agents):
        for j in range(num_agents):
            if i == j:
                distmatrix[i, j] = 0  # later turned to 0!
            else:
                distmatrix[i, j] = dist(xypos[i], xypos[j],proximity_weight)

    # pick min_neighbors neighbors with a probability equal to their relative euclidean distance
    edgelist = []
    degreelist = []
    
    for i in range(num_agents):
        distp = distmatrix[i]
        distp /= distp.sum()  # normalizing the probabilities

        if degreelist.count(i) < degree_seq[i]:
            try:
                alters = np.random.choice(num_agents, degree_seq[i], replace=False, p=distp)
                for j in alters:
                    edgelist.append([i, j])
                    degreelist.append(i)
                    #degreelist.append(j)
            except(ValueError):
                print(
                    "Please pick a lower value for the proximity weight. This value creates too many probability values of 0")

    G = nx.DiGraph()
    G.add_nodes_from([i for i in range(num_agents)])
    G.add_edges_from(edgelist)
    
    if return_positions:
        return G, xypos
    else:
        return G

def simulation_run(network,
                   bot_connectedness=.25,
                   bot_activation_rate=.25,
                   N=144,
                   K=12,
                   P=0,
                   return_activity_monitor=True,
                   return_graph=False,
                   max_ticks=100000,
                   seed=None):
    """
    This function
        1. Creates the Axelrod model as a NetworkX graph object with a bot
        2. Executes similarity biased influence between 
            a. the BOT and a randomly selected network neighbor (with p = bot_activation_rate)
            b. two randomly selected network neighbors (with p = 1-bot_activation_rate)
        3. Returns graph object when no further influence is possible (or after 100,000 ticks)
    """
    
    ## PHASE 1) INITIALIZATION
    
    # seed the run for replicability
    random.seed(seed)
    
    # generate the NetworkX graph object and intialize with F random categorical features with Q traits
    G = network #directed_spatial_random_graph()
    ds.initialize_attributes(G, realization="random_categorical", num_features=3, num_traits=3)
    
    # add the bot to the graph
    agentlist = list(G.nodes())
    G.add_node("bot")
    G.nodes["bot"]["f01"] = 99    # Unique bot trait, used to track the bot's effectiveness
    G.nodes["bot"]["f02"] = 0
    G.nodes["bot"]["f03"] = 0
    
    # connect the bot to a proportion 'bot_connectedness' of the graph
    friends_of_bot = random.sample(agentlist, int(bot_connectedness * N))
    for j in friends_of_bot:
        G.add_edge("bot",j)
    
    # calculate the dissimilarity on all edges
    calculator = ds.dissimilarity_calculator.select_calculator("hamming")
    calculator.calculate_dissimilarity_networkwide(G)

    # store the indices of direct and indirect contacts of the bot
    shortest_paths = nx.shortest_path_length(G,'bot')
    agents_l1 = [key for key, val in shortest_paths.items() if val == 1]
    agents_l2 = [key for key, val in shortest_paths.items() if val >= 2]
    
    # initialize ticks, stop variable, and tickwise dictionaries for output
    ticks = 0
    stop = False
    bot_trait_count = [dict(count_l1=len(agents_l1),
                            count_l2=len(agents_l2))]
    activity_monitor = dict(success=[],
                            i_is_bot=[])

    ## PHASE 2) SIMULATION
    
    while(not stop):
        ticks += 1

        # choose sending agent
        if random.random() > bot_activation_rate:
            agent_i = ds.select_focal_agent(G,"random",agentlist=agentlist)
            activity_monitor['i_is_bot'].append(False)
        else:
            agent_i = "bot"
            activity_monitor['i_is_bot'].append(True)

        # choose receiving agent
        agent_j = ["bot"]
        while agent_j == ["bot"]:
            agent_j = [(random.choice([neighbor for neighbor in G[agent_i]]))]

        # exert influence and store whether influence was successful 
        activity_monitor['success'].append(
            ds.influence_sim.spread_influence(G,"axelrod",agent_i,agent_j,"one-to-one",calculator)
        )
        
        # store the diffusion of the unique bot trait among first and second (or more) degree contacts
        bot_trait_count.append({'count_l1': len([1 for i in agents_l1 if G.nodes[i]['f01']==99]) / len(agents_l1),
                                'count_l2': len([1 for i in agents_l2 if G.nodes[i]['f01']==99]) / len(agents_l2)})

        # stop the execution if condition is true
        if(not any([True for i,j,d in G.edges.data('dist') if 0.1 < d < .9])
          or ticks > max_ticks):
            if(return_graph):
                return G
            if(return_activity_monitor):
                return bot_trait_count, activity_monitor
            else:
                return bot_trait_count
            stop = True

# function to generate the network figures for spatial random graphs
def gen_srg_fig(G, xypos):
    pos = {'bot': [0,0]}
    pos.update(dict(zip([i for i in range(len(G.nodes()))], xypos)))
    
    nodecol = ['r' if G.nodes[i]['f01'] == 99 else 'b' for i in G.nodes()]
    bin_col = plt.cm.get_cmap('binary', 4)
    edgecol = [bin_col(1 - G.edges[i]['dist']) for i in G.edges()]
    
    bot_contacts = []
    for i, j in G.edges():
        if i == 'bot':
            bot_contacts.append(j)
        if j == 'bot':
            bot_contacts.append(i)

    
    
    Gcopy = G.copy()
    #Gcopy.remove_edges_from([i for i in G.edges() if G.edges[i]['dist'] == 1])
    Gcopy = Gcopy.subgraph([i for i in Gcopy.nodes() if i != 'bot'])
    
    nx.draw_networkx_edges(Gcopy, pos=pos, edge_color=edgecol)
    nx.draw_networkx_nodes(Gcopy.subgraph([i for i in G.nodes() if i not in bot_contacts]), 
                           pos=pos, node_shape='o', node_size=75, node_color=nodecol)
    nx.draw_networkx_nodes(Gcopy.subgraph(bot_contacts), 
                           pos=pos, node_shape='^', node_size=75, node_color=nodecol)

With the functions defined above, we can create spatial random graphs, run a single simulation run with them, and plot the obtained graph. Nodes linked to the bot are shown as triangles.
